Can the euro be fixed?
Paris—Germany's finance minister, Wolfgang Schäuble, recently put the option of Greece exiting the euro on the table, hoping to send a signal that no member state can be exempt from the strict discipline of the currency union.
In fact, his proposal sparked a major debate over the principles that form the foundation of the euro, the euro's governance model, and the rationale for the euro's existence.
Two weeks before Wolfgang Schäuble's proposal, European leaders had already noticed a report on the future of the euro written by European Commission President Juncker and his colleagues from other EU institutions. However, the new debate over Greece led many policymakers to believe it was necessary to return to the original starting point.
At the same time, citizens are questioning why they should share a single currency?
Does this make sense? Can a consensus be reached on Greece's future?
A currency is like a nation; it requires a myth to establish it.
Traditional wisdom holds that the euro was the political price Germany paid for reunification.
In fact, Germany's reunification was merely the final step of an engineering project that had already taken shape in the 1980s to resolve a long-standing problem.
European governments strongly oppose floating exchange rates, considering them incompatible with the single market; yet they are unwilling to retain the monetary system dominated by the German central bank in the long term.
A truly European currency based on German principles seems to be the best solution.
In hindsight, Germany's reunification proved to be more of a curse than a blessing.
When exchange rates were locked in 1999, Germany was overvalued and facing economic difficulties; France was undervalued and experiencing economic prosperity.
In the following decade, the imbalance gradually formed between the resurgent Germany and countries experiencing credit booms due to low interest rates.
And with the outbreak of the 2008 global financial crisis, these conditions became the perfect breeding ground for a perfect storm.
No one knows what Europe would be like without the euro.
Will the fixed exchange rate system continue or collapse?
Will the German mark still be overvalued?
Would countries reintroduce trade barriers and end the single market?
Will a real estate bubble emerge in Spain?
Will there be more or fewer government reforms?
It is impossible to establish a baseline for a reverse analysis to assess the impact of the euro.
But this is certainly not a reason for complacency.
In the past 15 years, the economic performance of the eurozone has been disappointing, and its political system must bear the responsibility for this.
What really matters is whether a common European currency remains important for the future.
This issue is often avoided because the cost of leaving the euro is unimaginably high (and would be even higher if the eurozone's breakup were to occur during a crisis and exacerbate mutual tensions among member states).
Moreover, abolishing the euro might unleash the dark forces of nationalism and protectionism.
However, Kevin O'Rourke of Oxford University recently pointed out that this view is not sufficient.
Logically, this is equivalent to suggesting that a couple should stay married simply because the cost of divorce is too high.
So, does the euro still have a meaning?
Originally, people expected the euro to bring three major economic benefits.
People assumed that a currency union could promote economic integration and consolidate long-term growth in Europe.
On the contrary, trade and investment growth within the eurozone has been mediocre, and the growth potential has in fact been weakened.
This is partly because national governments have not taken further steps on the basis of monetary unification to build the eurozone into an economic superpower, but instead have tried to retain the remaining powers they have.
This might be politically logical, but it is economically worthless: Europe's huge internal market is one of its main assets, and therefore the opportunity to strengthen the internal market must never be wasted.
Secondly, people hoped the euro would become one of the major international currencies (especially considering that few countries meet the necessary legal, market, and policy institutions).
According to the latest data from the European Central Bank, this hope has basically been realized.
The euro's international use ranks second to the dollar, an achievement that helps Europe continue to influence the global economic order rather than becoming an irrelevant entity.
Third, people (not without naivety) believed that the institutions underpinning the euro could improve the overall quality of economic policy, as if the level of European policy were inherently higher than that of national policies.
After the 2008 global financial crisis, a severe test came: the eurozone overestimated the fiscal dimension of the crisis and underestimated its financial dimension, hence performing worse than the United States and the United Kingdom.
If the euro is to bring prosperity, further reforms in policy institutions are essential.
But the formulation and implementation of an agenda must be based on a broad consensus on the nature of the issues.
The ongoing debate over Greece shows that Europe is far from reaching a consensus: participating countries have conflicting analyses of the root causes of the debt crisis, and thus their proposed solutions are also contradictory.
Harvard's Richard Cooper once observed that in the early stages of international public health cooperation, the governance of global diseases was greatly hindered by the different transmission patterns existing in various countries.
All countries favor joint action, but they cannot form a consistent plan because they disagree on how infectious diseases spread from one country to another.
This is the problem the eurozone faces today.
Fortunately, this problem is not unsolvable, as major reforms such as the establishment of the European Stability Mechanism and the launch of the banking union have already demonstrated.
Disagreement has not prevented the European Central Bank from taking decisive action, indicating that institutional governance does indeed matter.
But the fact that reforms and actions only recently began and were implemented under the pressure of a severe crisis has made us clearly aware of the difficulty of reaching a consensus.
Europe can no longer delay and pretend.
Eurozone members must develop a unified agenda on governance and political reform to transform the currency union into an engine of prosperity; otherwise, they will continue to sink into repeated disputes and crises until citizens lose patience or markets lose confidence.
Clarity is a prerequisite for serious discussion and sweeping reforms.
Now, all major stakeholders have an obligation to clearly define what they consider indispensable, what they find unacceptable, and what they are prepared to offer in exchange for what they want.
